                    <title>Name: Legacy Pairing (not sur…</title>
                    <link rel="alternate" href="http://coderetreat.org/xn/detail/6456126:Comment:32800"/>
                                        <id>tag:coderetreat.org,2013-12-14:6456126:Comment:32800</id>
                                        <updated>2013-12-14T23:28:34.621Z</updated>
                    
                                            <author>
                            <name>Marc Bless</name>
                            <uri>http://coderetreat.org/profile/MarcBless</uri>
                        </author>
                    
                    <summary type="html">
                        &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Name:&lt;/strong&gt; Legacy Pairing (not sure if the name fits very well)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &quot;Solve the problem as quickly and dirty as possible. Do not write clean code, do not create a good design, just forget anything you’ve ever learned about inner code quality. Simply get this thing running!&quot; After 15 minutes, tell the pairs that one of their halfs will be gone and replace them with someone from another pair as the new guy who is now responsible for clean code,…&lt;/p&gt;                    </summary>

                                            <content type="html">
                            &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Name:&lt;/strong&gt; Legacy Pairing (not sure if the name fits very well)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &quot;Solve the problem as quickly and dirty as possible. Do not write clean code, do not create a good design, just forget anything you’ve ever learned about inner code quality. Simply get this thing running!&quot; After 15 minutes, tell the pairs that one of their halfs will be gone and replace them with someone from another pair as the new guy who is now responsible for clean code, testing, etc.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Learning Goal:&lt;/strong&gt; it&#039;s nearly impossible to transform the dirty code of the first 15 minutes into something more clean within the next 25 minutes. Socially, &quot;old&quot; guys in the pairs tend to keep their dirty code. &quot;Broken window&quot; effect can be observed: an existing dirty code base continues to grow.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Preferred Session:&lt;/strong&gt; afternoon, maybe right after lunch as an energetic activity&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Notes:&lt;/strong&gt; I&#039;ve written a short blog post on this activity &lt;a href=&quot;http://agilecoach.de/2013-12-14/creating-legacy-behavior-in-15-minutes/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://agilecoach.de/2013-12-14/creating-legacy-behavior-in-15-minutes/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;                        </content>
                    
                                    </entry>
